AB  - The long history of Terra Australis describes a space sketched in lines of speculation, ambition and multiple desire. Even at the end of the eighteenth century – after Cook’s exemplary curiosity and minute mapping produced the fabled space of Terra Australis as a place of English settlement and incarceration – knowledge of the new continent of Australia remained provisional and speculative. As was the case in its earliest incarnations, the representation of Terra Australis responds to contemporary preoccupations and imaginative investments, in this case the intermeshing late eighteenth-century realities of slavery, anti-slavery, trade, transportation and colonialism. Mary Ann Parker’s account of Australia shortly after European settlement reveals a network of such influences at work in her encounters with the landscape and culture of the new settlement. The Voyage Around the World (1795) positions Port Jackson at its narrative centre, but Parker’s perception of New South Wales is shaped by a broader circulation of people, information and ideas through the Atlantic. Parker’s approach to the colonial project at New South Wales is formed through anterior networks of hospitality and commerce connecting trading communities and colonial settlements along global travel routes. These material networks provide powerful cultural and ideological models for the voyageuse: the mediating values of Parker’s text are the forms of politeness and global hospitality she enjoys in the West Indies and the Cape, complicated by the ethical dilemmas of enforced labour. © Anne M. Scott, Alfred Hiatt, Claire McIlroy and Christopher Wortham 2011.
